[3] China, fatalities, research agenda - National Health Services press conference 4 Feb 2020
Date: 4 Feb 2020
Source: China National Health Commission press conference, 4 Feb 2020 [in Chinese, mach. trans. edited/excerpted]
http://www.nhc.gov.cn/xcs/yqfkdt/202002/35990d56cfcb43f4a70d7f9703b113c0.shtml


Key points:
As of 24:00 3 Feb 2020, the cumulative number of cases nationwide was 20 438, with cumulative deaths at 425. National mortality rate calculated at 2.1%.

In Hubei, there were 414 reported deaths, representing 97% of the country's fatalities. Calculated mortality rate in Hubei Province is 3.1%.

In Wuhan, there were 313 reported deaths, representing 74% of the country's fatalities. Calculated mortality rate in Wuhan is 4.9%.

The calculated fatality rate in other provinces is 0.16%. While the number of cases is not small in other provinces, the case fatality rate is quite low. This may reflect that most cases have mild presentations.

Most fatal cases are male (2/3), with females representing 1/3. Most cases are elderly with more than 80% over 60 years old. More than 75% have one or more pre-existing co-morbidities including cardiovascular diseases, diabetes and malignancies in some of the patients. [It was emphasized that elderly individuals [defined as 60 years of age or older] with pre-existing disease are at high risk from any type of pneumonia, not just the 2019-nCoV pneumonia.]

In explaining why there was a higher fatality rate in Wuhan, it was mentioned that, early on, there were insufficient critical care beds to cover the more serious presentations, and patients were admitted to 3 designated hospitals with a total of 110 critical care beds. Other critical cases were admitted to 20 other medical institutions, not all with tertiary level care. Now, independent hospitals with tertiary level care are part of the network presently used. A shortage of well-trained critical care physicians and management was also mentioned. This is currently being addressed locally as well as nationally.

In response to query on ongoing research: A research team with 12 departments has been established along with a team of 14 academicians and experts with academician Zhong Nanshan as team leader. 16 research projects have been identified with a focus on virus traceability, drug research and development, vaccine development, and testing. Reagents and experimental animal models have been deployed. Aiming at scientific and technological innovations, 2 major projects include testing new drugs and the prevention and treatment of major infectious diseases.

There's an integration of scientific research with clinical needs and prevention and control practices. There was the rapid isolation and identification of the novel coronavirus, with whole genome sequencing and rapid sharing with the international community. They have developed nucleic acid diagnostic reagents and are actively engaged in the development of serologic testing. With respect to drug research, selection of drugs with potential anti-nCoV effects are under study along with curative effect of these drugs. They are also working on vaccine development against the nCoV.

There was a discussion on the cited "cure" [surely this should be "recovery". - Mod.SH] rate. At present, there isn't a clear formula for calculating the cure rate. The average time for hospitalization to discharge nationwide is a little more than 9 days. The range is 5 days (Hainan province) to 12.75 days (Guangdong province). An outlier is Hubei where the average time to discharge is 20 days. Explanation for outlying Hubei: 1st, more severe patients; 2nd, more stringent discharge criteria set by Wuhan City; a patient must have 2 negative nucleic acid tests with an interval of 24 hours after clinical symptoms disappear.

