[4] Selected media reports of transmission outside of China:
A: Malaysia ex Singapore
Date: 4 Feb 2020
Source: Malay Mail [edited]
https://www.malaymail.com/news/malaysia/2020/02/04/selangor-man-is-first-malaysian-to-test-positive-for-wuhan-virus/1834350


A Malaysian man has tested positive for the Wuhan virus, the 1st local to date, said health minister Datuk Seri Dzulkefly Ahmad at a press conference today [4 Feb 2020].

Dzulkefly said the man traveled to Singapore from [16 to 23 Jan 2020] to attend a meeting which had several foreign delegates, including from China. "He returned to Malaysia on [23 Jan 2020], and on [29 Jan 2020], he received treatment at a private hospital because of fever and cough. "Then, he was referred to the Sungai Buloh Hospital on [2 Feb 2020], and was admitted to the isolation ward. He was confirmed for the 2019-nCoV yesterday [3 Feb 2020]," Dzulkefly said. He said the 41 year old patient was stable, and the Health Ministry has contacted its Singaporean counterpart, which confirmed that it has begun tracing those who had been in contact with him.

The minister also disclosed another confirmed infection, a 63 year old Chinese national from Wuhan who landed at Kuala Lumpur International Airport (KLIA) on [18 Jan 2020]. Dzulkefly said he initially had light fever and received outpatient treatment at a private hospital in Kuala Lumpur. His case was flagged to the ministry, which then sequestered him at his home for a 2-week observation period. "On [2 Feb 2020], his fever continued, and he was then admitted to Kuala Lumpur Hospital (HKL) for further treatment. The lab test result showed him to be positive for 2019-nCov on [3 Feb 2020]. "The patient is currently in the isolation ward and is in stable condition," Dzulkefly added.

The 2 newest cases bring Malaysia's total 2019-nCoV infections to 10, 5 of whom had been patients-under-investigation, and the rest were those who had been in close contact. Of the latter 5, 4 are in Hospital Sungai Buloh and one is in Johor's Hospital Permai. Aside from the Malaysian, all the confirmed cases involve Chinese nationals.

The minister said 213 PUIs [persons under investigation?] were screened between [10 Jan 2020] and the evening of [3 Feb 2020], involving 122 Malaysians, 8 Chinese nationals, and one each from Australia, South Korea, Jordan, Brazil and Thailand. Health authorities have cleared 188, while 20 PUIs are awaiting results of their laboratory tests. Of the 36 individuals located through contact tracing, 27 were negative, and 4 are pending test results.

