B. Singapore local transmission
Date: 4 Feb 2020
Source: Straits Times [edited]
https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/singapore-confirms-first-cases-of-local-coronavirus-transmission-what-we-know-about


- Singapore confirms 1st case of local coronavirus transmission
- What we know about the 6 new cases
- In total, there are now 24 confirmed cases here.

Here's what we know about the 6 new cases:
1. A 28 year old Singaporean resident who works as a sales staff member at Yong Thai Hang, a Chinese health products shop in Lavender. The shop serves mainly Chinese tourists. She has no recent travel history to China. She developed a sore throat and fever last Wednesday [29 Jan 2020]. She was taken to Tan Tock Seng Hospital the next day [30 Jan 2020] but was discharged from hospital after her chest x-ray result came back negative for pneumonia. She did not leave her home in Jalan Bukit Merah from last Friday [31 Jan 2020] to Sunday [2 Feb 2020]. She was admitted to the Singapore General Hospital (SGH) on Monday [3 Feb 2020].

2. A 48 year old Singaporean who also works at Yong Thai Hang. She lives in Hougang Street 61 and has no recent travel history to China. She reported symptoms on 25 Jan 2020 and was admitted to the National Centre for Infectious Diseases (NCID) on Monday [27 Jan 2020].

3. A 44 year old Indonesian woman who is the maid of the 28 year old Yong Thai Hang employee who was infected with the virus. She lives with her employer in her home in Jalan Bukit Merah. She reported symptoms on Sunday [2 Feb 2020] and had not left the residence since then. She was admitted to SGH on Monday [3 Feb 2020]. She has no recent travel history to China.

4. A 32 year old Singaporean who has no recent travel history in China. She is a tour guide who took groups to Yong Thai Hang. She did not show any symptoms when she went to NCID on Monday [3 Feb 2020]. She was immediately isolated and is now warded in an isolation room in the centre. She tested positive for the virus on Tuesday [4 Feb 2020].

5. A Singaporean evacuated from Wuhan last Thursday [30 Jan 2020] on a specially arranged Scoot flight. The Singaporean did not have symptoms when boarding the flight and was quarantined after landing in Singapore. The person tested positive for the coronavirus on Monday [3 Feb 2020] even though there were no symptoms. The patient is now warded in an isolation room at NCID.

6. Also, a Singaporean evacuated from Wuhan on the Scoot flight last Thursday [30 Jan 2020]. The Singaporean did not have symptoms when boarding the flight and was quarantined after landing in Singapore. The person tested positive for the coronavirus on Monday [3 Feb 2020] even though there were no symptoms. The patient is warded in an isolation room at NCID.

